zed Blackness, she examines a vibrant world of nineteenth-century US subterranean literature that includes Black radical manifestos, anarchist periodicals, sensationalist exposés of the urban underworld, manuals for sex magic, and the initiation rites of secret societies. Cohen finds that the undergrounds in this literature offer sites of political possibility that exceed the familiar framework of resistance, suggesting that nineteenth-century undergrounds can inspire new modes of world-making and world-breaking for a time when this world feels increasingly untenable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual lifey19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismy19th century. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryy19th centuryzUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and literaturexHistoryy19th centuryzUnited States. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.